article.headline: California 84, Arizona State 82
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Richard Midgley hit a couple of big 3-pointers in the second half but it was an off-balance layup along the baseline that was the difference. After Martin Smith missed a 15-footer, Midgley got the loose ball and scored the layup with 2.8 seconds left to lift California (12-9, 5-6 Pac-10) to an 84-82 victory over Arizona State on Saturday night. It was California's fourth victory in five games. "I saw Marty pull up for the shot and my man just left me and I just crashed in hoping the ball would come to me," Midgley said. "It came to me and I kind of just threw it up and it went in." Arizona State (16-7, 5-6 Pac-10) called a time-out with 2.2 seconds left and then Midgley knocked the in-bounds pass out of bounds with 1.4 seconds remaining. Bryson Krueger threw a pass on the ensuing in-bounds play to Ike Diogu, who missed a 12-footer on the baseline as time expired. "We were down early but I never saw panic in our team. Our team kept talking about working," said California coach Ben Braun. Diogu, who had 35 points and seven rebounds, had tied the game at 82 with a layup with 26.6 seconds left. The lead changed hands three times after Rod Benson made one of two free throws to give the Golden Bears a 70-69 advantage with about five minutes left. Benson led five Bears in double figures with 20 points and had eight rebounds. Midgley added 15 points. "In the second half we really turned the tide by increasing our pressure," said Braun. "I thought we handled their pressure better in the second half. We got the ball where we needed to get to." California made 17 of 25 shots in the second half, including 11 of its first 14, as it erased a 13-point deficit in the first 20 minutes. "They shoot almost 70 percent on us and they get second chance points," said Arizona State coach Rob Evans. "We told them during the time out to box out. It boils down to taking care of details and we didn't take care of details in critical situations." California out rebounded Arizona State 25-14 on the defensive end. "Every time we come in and we are talking about a loss, it boils down to one thing -- defensive rebounding," said Evans. Dominic McGuire, Martin Smith and Marquise Kately all scored 10 points for California. Serge Angounou hit his third 3-pointer of the season with 57.7 seconds left to give Arizona State an 80-79 lead but David Paris answered with a driving layup and subsequent free throw for California. Kevin Kruger scored 15 points for Arizona State. Angounou added 15 points. Diogu scored a career-high 39 points in Thursday's win over Stanford. It was the first time Diogu has scored 30 points in back-to-back games.
